[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837797326994&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837797326994&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

eckert@medusa.informatik.uni-erlangen.de (Toerless Eckert) writes:

&gt;There are no advantages in using alternate DE servers to uunet with
&gt;the current scheme. The problem that must be solved in this respect is
&gt;to allow non US connected networks into the DNS (especially the
&gt;IN-ADDR.ARPA zones). If that is done, we may well drop the current
&gt;scheme and have one common DE zone.

For the .de zone there is no problem at all. Just include all data even
for hosts and sites without connectivity. Who is going to stop you?
On what grounds?

For in-addr.arpa this is a real problem because it lives in the .arpa
domain and NS records have to live in the in-addr.arpa zone. This problem
has been raised with IAB, NSF and within IETF. So I hope it will be resolved
(no pun intended) soon. 

In the meantime Germany can put all their forward references in *one*
zone. Of course mcsun.eu.net will be happy to run a secondary server.

Daniel
-- 
Daniel Karrenberg                    Future Net:  &lt;dfk@cwi.nl&gt;
